<item>
 <title>Is the Unipolar Moment Over?</title>
 <link>http://www.brown.edu/Departments/Political_Theory_Project/janus/events/lectures/is_the_unipolar_moment_over</link>
 <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-type-datetime field-field-je-date&quot;&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;
                      &lt;div class=&quot;field-label-inline-first&quot;&gt;
              Date:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
                    &lt;span class=&quot;date-display-single&quot;&gt;Wednesday, November 28, 2012 - &lt;span class=&quot;date-display-start&quot;&gt;4:00pm&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;date-display-separator&quot;&gt; - &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;date-display-end&quot;&gt;6:00pm&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;        &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;field field-type-text field-field-je-speakers&quot;&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;
                      &lt;div class=&quot;field-label-inline-first&quot;&gt;
              Speakers:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
                    Robert Kagan and Charles Kupchan        &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After the fall of the Soviet Union, Francis Fukuyama famously declared that it was “the end of history,” a Pax Americana with the U.S. presiding over global democratization. September 11th, two wars, and a financial crisis later, structural weaknesses in the U.S. economy coupled with the rise of economic challengers like China and India lead to the question: is American hegemony in decline?&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
